-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Acts — Part 3 (Chapters 13–18)
-- 3 difficulties × 6 chapters = 96 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 18
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 30
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 48
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 13–15 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 13, 'kids', 1, 'Who sent Barnabas and Saul on their first missionary journey?', 'The Holy Ghost told the church at Antioch to send them', 'The Roman emperor commanded them to go', 'Peter asked them to travel', 'They decided on their own', 'a', 'Acts 13:2-4 — "The Holy Ghost said, Separate me Barnabas and Saul for the work whereunto I have called them... So they, being sent forth by the Holy Ghost, departed."'),
('Acts', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What happened to a sorcerer named Elymas when he tried to stop Paul from preaching?', 'He became blind for a time', 'He ran away in fear', 'He fell asleep', 'He turned into a stone', 'a', 'Acts 13:11 — "And now, behold, the hand of the Lord is upon thee, and thou shalt be blind, not seeing the sun for a season. And immediately there fell on him a mist and a darkness."'),
('Acts', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What did Paul and Barnabas tell the Jews who rejected the gospel?', 'We turn to the Gentiles, for so the Lord has commanded us', 'We will come back next week', 'We are going home to Jerusalem', 'We will ask the Romans for help', 'a', 'Acts 13:46 — "Then Paul and Barnabas waxed bold, and said... seeing ye put it from you, and judge yourselves unworthy of everlasting life, lo, we turn to the Gentiles."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 13, 'teens', 1, 'What major transition occurs with Saul''s name in chapter 13?', 'Luke begins using "Paul" instead of "Saul" — his Roman name — marking the shift from the Jewish mission to the Gentile mission', 'Saul changed his name because he was ashamed', 'A Roman governor renamed him', 'The church voted to change his name', 'a', 'Acts 13:9 — "Then Saul, (who also is called Paul,) filled with the Holy Ghost..." From this point Luke uses "Paul." Jews commonly had both Hebrew and Roman/Greek names. The switch signals Paul''s Gentile-focused ministry.'),
('Acts', 13, 'teens', 2, 'What was the main point of Paul''s sermon in the synagogue at Antioch in Pisidia?', 'He traced Israel''s history from the patriarchs to David, then proclaimed that Jesus is the promised Saviour — crucified, buried, and raised from the dead, and through Him forgiveness of sins is offered', 'He told the people to follow the law of Moses more strictly', 'He preached about the coming destruction of Rome', 'He encouraged them to move to Jerusalem', 'a', 'Acts 13:23,30,38 — "Of this man''s seed hath God according to his promise raised unto Israel a Saviour, Jesus... But God raised him from the dead... through this man is preached unto you the forgiveness of sins."'),
('Acts', 13, 'teens', 3, 'What Scripture did Paul quote to prove the resurrection of Jesus?', 'Psalm 16:10 — "Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption" — arguing that David died and decayed, but Jesus was raised and did not see corruption', 'Genesis 1:1 about creation', 'Exodus 20 about the Ten Commandments', 'Proverbs 3 about trusting the Lord', 'a', 'Acts 13:35-37 — "Wherefore he saith also in another psalm, Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption. For David... fell on sleep, and was laid unto his fathers, and saw corruption: But he, whom God raised again, saw no corruption."'),
('Acts', 13, 'teens', 4, 'How did the Gentiles react when Paul said he was turning to them?', 'The Gentiles were glad and glorified the word of the Lord, and as many as were ordained to eternal life believed', 'The Gentiles were angry and rejected Paul', 'The Gentiles ignored Paul and walked away', 'The Gentiles asked Paul to come back next year', 'a', 'Acts 13:48 — "And when the Gentiles heard this, they were glad, and glorified the word of the Lord: and as many as were ordained to eternal life believed."'),
('Acts', 13, 'teens', 5, 'What happened to Paul and Barnabas after the Jews stirred up persecution?', 'They shook off the dust of their feet and went to Iconium, but the disciples were filled with joy and the Holy Ghost', 'They returned to Jerusalem in defeat', 'They gave up and stopped preaching', 'They joined the synagogue to avoid trouble', 'a', 'Acts 13:51-52 — "But they shook off the dust of their feet against them, and came unto Iconium. And the disciples were filled with joy, and with the Holy Ghost."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 1, 'How does the Antioch church''s commissioning of Barnabas and Saul (13:1-4) establish a pattern for missionary sending?', 'The commissioning combines prophetic direction ("the Holy Ghost said"), communal discernment (church leaders fasting and praying), and formal commission (laying on of hands). The mission is Spirit-initiated, church-confirmed, and community-supported — not an individual venture. This threefold pattern becomes the model for all subsequent missionary sending', 'Barnabas and Saul decided on their own', 'Only the apostles in Jerusalem could send missionaries', 'The commissioning was a formality with no significance', 'a', 'Acts 13:1-4 — "As they ministered to the Lord, and fasted, the Holy Ghost said, Separate me Barnabas and Saul." Three elements: Spirit''s call (v.2), church''s confirmation through prayer/fasting (v.3), and formal commissioning (laying on of hands, v.3). "Sent forth by the Holy Ghost" (v.4) — the Spirit is the primary sender.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 2, 'How does Paul''s Antioch-in-Pisidia sermon (13:16-41) parallel Peter''s Pentecost sermon while adapting it for a diaspora synagogue audience?', 'Both follow the same kerygmatic structure: Israel''s history leading to Jesus, His death and resurrection, Scripture proofs (both cite Psalm 16), and a call to respond. But Paul adapts by adding more historical review (patriarchs, exodus, judges, Saul, David), invoking "the children of the stock of Abraham" (v.26), and introducing justification language: "by him all that believe are justified from all things, from which ye could not be justified by the law of Moses" (v.39)', 'Paul''s sermon is completely different from Peter''s', 'Both sermons are identical word for word', 'Paul only quoted from the book of Moses', 'a', 'Acts 13:16-41 — Paul''s sermon mirrors Acts 2 in structure but adds the Abraham-to-David historical arc (vv.17-22) for a diaspora audience that valued patriarchal heritage. The justification statement (v.39) goes beyond Peter''s sermon, introducing Pauline soteriology in embryonic form.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 3, 'What does "as many as were ordained to eternal life believed" (13:48) teach about election and faith?', 'The verse presents divine election ("ordained" = tetagmenoi, meaning appointed/placed in order) and human faith ("believed") in a single sentence without resolving the tension. God''s prior appointment and the human act of believing are both affirmed. Luke does not present this as contradictory but as complementary — those whom God appointed came to faith', 'Only human decision determines salvation', 'God forces people to believe against their will', 'The verse is about political ordination', 'a', 'Acts 13:48 — "As many as were ordained (tetagmenoi) to eternal life believed." The perfect passive participle "ordained" points to a prior divine action. Luke states the fact without philosophical explanation. Both sovereignty and faith are affirmed: God ordains, people believe. The tension is left unresolved.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of Paul''s citation of Isaiah 49:6 ("a light of the Gentiles") in 13:47?', 'Paul applies the Servant Song of Isaiah 49:6 — originally about Israel/the Servant — to his own Gentile mission. This is remarkable: Paul sees himself and Barnabas participating in the Servant''s mission of bringing light to the nations. The church''s mission is the continuation of the Servant''s work — extending Christ''s light to the ends of the earth', 'Paul was misquoting Isaiah', 'Isaiah 49 is only about the nation of Israel', 'The citation was irrelevant to the situation', 'a', 'Acts 13:47 — "For so hath the Lord commanded us, saying, I have set thee to be a light of the Gentiles, that thou shouldest be for salvation unto the ends of the earth." Paul applies Isaiah 49:6 (the Servant''s commission) to his apostolic calling — identifying the church''s Gentile mission with the Servant''s universal vocation.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 5, 'How does Paul''s statement about justification (13:39) anticipate his later epistolary theology?', 'Paul introduces justification language unprecedented in Acts: "by him all that believe are justified from all things, from which ye could not be justified by the law of Moses." This is embryonic Galatians/Romans theology — justification through faith in Christ accomplishes what the Mosaic law could not. It is Paul''s earliest recorded articulation of justification by faith', 'Paul never discussed justification in Acts', 'This verse contradicts his later letters', 'Justification language was common in all apostolic preaching', 'a', 'Acts 13:39 — "And by him all that believe are justified from all things, from which ye could not be justified by the law of Moses." This anticipates Romans 3:20-28 and Galatians 2:16. The law''s inability and Christ''s sufficiency are both stated. Luke shows Paul''s theology emerging in his preaching before his letters.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 6, 'What does Paul''s synagogue strategy (going to Jews first, then Gentiles) reveal about his missionary method?', 'Paul consistently goes to the synagogue first in each city — not because the gospel belongs exclusively to Jews but because of covenant priority ("to the Jew first," Romans 1:16) and practical strategy (God-fearers in synagogues were receptive bridge populations). When Jews reject, Paul turns to Gentiles — a pattern repeated throughout his journeys', 'Paul went to synagogues because Gentiles would not listen', 'The synagogue strategy was accidental', 'Paul only preached to Jews throughout Acts', 'a', 'Acts 13:14,46 — Paul enters the synagogue, preaches, is rejected by some Jews, and turns to Gentiles. This pattern repeats in Iconium (14:1), Thessalonica (17:1-5), Corinth (18:4-6), and Ephesus (19:8-9). The theological rationale: Romans 1:16 "to the Jew first, and also to the Greek."'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 7, 'What does Paul''s application of Psalm 2:7 and Isaiah 55:3 to the resurrection reveal about his hermeneutic?', 'Paul reads Psalm 2:7 ("Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee") as fulfilled in the resurrection — God''s declaration of Jesus as Son is publicly enacted by raising Him from the dead. Isaiah 55:3 ("the sure mercies of David") is interpreted as the Davidic covenant promises being secured through an incorruptible risen Messiah. Both are eschatological-Christological readings', 'Paul interpreted these texts literally only', 'These psalms have no messianic meaning', 'The resurrection is not connected to Old Testament prophecy', 'a', 'Acts 13:33-34 — Paul cites Psalm 2:7 ("this day have I begotten thee") for the resurrection and Isaiah 55:3 ("the sure mercies of David") for the permanence of resurrection life. His hermeneutic: OT promises to David find their ultimate fulfilment in the risen Christ, not in David''s mortal dynasty.'),
('Acts', 13, 'adults', 8, 'How does Paul''s warning from Habakkuk 1:5 (Acts 13:40-41) function in his sermon?', 'Paul ends with a prophetic warning: Habakkuk warned Israel that God was doing something unbelievable (the Babylonian invasion) that sceptics would reject. Paul applies this to the gospel — God is again doing an "unbelievable" work (salvation through a crucified Messiah) and those who despise it will perish. The warning transforms the sermon from invitation to urgent ultimatum', 'The Habakkuk quotation was irrelevant padding', 'Paul was threatening military invasion', 'The warning applied only to Habakkuk''s original audience', 'a', 'Acts 13:40-41 — "Beware therefore, lest that come upon you, which is spoken of in the prophets; Behold, ye despisers, and wonder, and perish: for I work a work in your days, a work which ye shall in no wise believe, though a man declare it unto you." The unbelievable work shifts from Babylon to the cross — scepticism brings the same judgment.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 14 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 14, 'kids', 1, 'What happened to a crippled man in Lystra when Paul saw that he had faith?', 'Paul told him to stand up on his feet, and the man leaped and walked', 'Paul gave him a pair of crutches', 'The man slowly learned to walk over many weeks', 'Nothing happened to the man', 'a', 'Acts 14:9-10 — "The same heard Paul speak: who stedfastly beholding him, and perceiving that he had faith to be healed, Said with a loud voice, Stand upright on thy feet. And he leaped and walked."'),
('Acts', 14, 'kids', 2, 'What did the people of Lystra try to do to Paul and Barnabas after the healing?', 'They tried to worship them as gods, calling Barnabas Jupiter and Paul Mercury', 'They threw them a party', 'They gave them gold and silver', 'They asked them to become kings', 'a', 'Acts 14:11-12 — "The gods are come down to us in the likeness of men. And they called Barnabas, Jupiter; and Paul, Mercurius, because he was the chief speaker."'),
('Acts', 14, 'kids', 3, 'What did some angry people do to Paul in Lystra?', 'They stoned him and dragged him out of the city thinking he was dead', 'They put him in prison', 'They chased him with swords', 'They burned his tent', 'a', 'Acts 14:19 — "And there came thither certain Jews from Antioch and Iconium, who persuaded the people, and, having stoned Paul, drew him out of the city, supposing he had been dead."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 14, 'teens', 1, 'How did Paul and Barnabas react when the people tried to worship them as gods?', 'They tore their clothes and rushed into the crowd shouting "We also are men of like passions with you" and urged them to turn from vanities to the living God', 'They accepted the worship graciously', 'They quietly left the city', 'They asked the people to worship God instead of them at the temple of Jupiter', 'a', 'Acts 14:14-15 — "Which when the apostles, Barnabas and Paul, heard of, they rent their clothes, and ran in among the people, crying out, And saying, Sirs, why do ye these things? We also are men of like passions with you, and preach unto you that ye should turn from these vanities unto the living God."'),
('Acts', 14, 'teens', 2, 'What did Paul and Barnabas tell the new believers about entering the kingdom of God?', 'We must through much tribulation enter into the kingdom of God', 'The kingdom of God is easy and requires no sacrifice', 'Tribulation is a sign of God''s displeasure', 'Only people without problems can enter the kingdom', 'a', 'Acts 14:22 — "Confirming the souls of the disciples, and exhorting them to continue in the faith, and that we must through much tribulation enter into the kingdom of God."'),
('Acts', 14, 'teens', 3, 'What did Paul and Barnabas do in every church they had started?', 'They ordained elders in every church, prayed with fasting, and commended them to the Lord', 'They stayed permanently in each city', 'They left without appointing any leaders', 'They asked each church to send money to Jerusalem', 'a', 'Acts 14:23 — "And when they had ordained them elders in every church, and had prayed with fasting, they commended them to the Lord, on whom they believed."'),
('Acts', 14, 'teens', 4, 'What did Paul do after being stoned and left for dead outside Lystra?', 'As the disciples stood around him, he rose up and came back into the city, and the next day went with Barnabas to Derbe', 'He was carried to Jerusalem for healing', 'He stayed in bed for several months', 'He returned home to Tarsus permanently', 'a', 'Acts 14:20 — "Howbeit, as the disciples stood round about him, he rose up, and came into the city: and the next day he departed with Barnabas to Derbe."'),
('Acts', 14, 'teens', 5, 'What report did Paul and Barnabas give when they returned to Antioch?', 'They gathered the church together and reported all that God had done with them, and how He had opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles', 'They complained about how difficult the journey had been', 'They asked for more money and supplies', 'They said the Gentiles were not interested in the gospel', 'a', 'Acts 14:27 — "And when they were come, and had gathered the church together, they rehearsed all that God had done with them, and how he had opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 1, 'How does Paul''s speech at Lystra (14:15-17) differ from his synagogue sermons, and what does this reveal about contextualised evangelism?', 'At Lystra, Paul addresses pagans with no knowledge of Scripture — so he starts with natural revelation: God as Creator, provider of rain and fruitful seasons, and sustainer of life. He makes no Old Testament citations. This shows Paul adapting his message to his audience: Jews hear Scripture; pagans hear creation theology. The core message (turn to the living God) is the same; the entry point differs', 'Paul always preached the same way to everyone', 'Paul abandoned Scripture when speaking to pagans', 'The Lystra speech had no theological content', 'a', 'Acts 14:15-17 — Paul appeals to "the living God, which made heaven, and earth, and the sea" and to God''s providential witness through "rain from heaven, and fruitful seasons." Compare with the Athens speech (17:22-31) — both start with creation, not covenant. Paul models 1 Corinthians 9:22: "I am made all things to all men."'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 2, 'What does the rapid swing from worship to stoning at Lystra reveal about the nature of popular acclaim?', 'The same crowd that tried to worship Paul as a god was persuaded to stone him — showing the volatility and fickleness of popular opinion. Human praise is unreliable and dangerous. The episode echoes Jesus'' triumphal entry followed by "Crucify him!" within a week. Paul later reflects: "If I yet pleased men, I should not be the servant of Christ" (Galatians 1:10)', 'The crowd was different people', 'Paul provoked the stoning intentionally', 'Worship and violence are unrelated', 'a', 'Acts 14:11-13 vs 14:19 — From "the gods have come down" to "having stoned Paul, drew him out of the city." The swing from adulation to murder took only outside agitators to catalyse. Luke shows that popular praise is worthless — the same voices that deify you can destroy you.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 3, 'What does "we must through much tribulation enter into the kingdom of God" (14:22) teach about the relationship between suffering and salvation?', 'Tribulation is not an obstacle to the kingdom but the pathway through which believers enter it. Paul, freshly stoned at Lystra, teaches not prosperity but a theology of the cross — suffering is the normal Christian experience, not an aberration. This prepares new believers for persecution and prevents disillusionment when it comes', 'Tribulation can be avoided with enough faith', 'Only Paul was expected to suffer', 'Suffering means God has abandoned the believer', 'a', 'Acts 14:22 — "We must (dei = divine necessity) through much tribulation enter into the kingdom of God." Paul teaches this immediately after being stoned — his wounds are his credentials. The "must" (dei) makes tribulation a theological necessity, not an optional experience.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 4, 'What does the appointment of elders (14:23) reveal about Paul''s ecclesiology?', 'Paul established local leadership in every new church — he did not create permanent dependency on apostolic presence. Elders (presbuteroi) provided ongoing pastoral care. The combination of prayer, fasting, and commending to the Lord shows that church planting includes structural organisation, spiritual dependence, and eventual apostolic withdrawal. Healthy churches are self-governing under local leaders', 'Paul stayed in each church permanently', 'Elders were only appointed in Jerusalem', 'New churches did not need organised leadership', 'a', 'Acts 14:23 — "When they had ordained them elders in every church, and had prayed with fasting, they commended them to the Lord." Paul''s pattern: evangelise, establish, organise, entrust, depart. The elders are "commended to the Lord" — ultimate dependence is on Christ, not on the apostle.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 5, 'How does the Lystra healing parallel the Beautiful Gate healing in Acts 3?', 'Both involve a man lame from birth, healed through faith by an apostle''s command. Both lead to a crowd response (worship/amazement) and a theological speech correcting the crowd''s misunderstanding. Both result in opposition. Luke draws deliberate parallels between Peter''s ministry (Acts 3) and Paul''s (Acts 14), validating Paul''s apostolic authority as equal to Peter''s', 'The two healings are unrelated', 'Only Peter performed genuine miracles', 'Paul copied Peter''s method', 'a', 'Acts 14:8-10 parallels Acts 3:1-10: lame from birth (3:2/14:8), faith perceived (3:4/14:9), command to rise (3:6/14:10), leaping response (3:8/14:10). Luke validates Paul''s apostleship by mirroring Peter''s signs.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological significance of Paul''s statement that God "suffered all nations to walk in their own ways" (14:16)?', 'Paul acknowledges a period of divine forbearance when God allowed the nations to follow their own paths without the revelation given to Israel (cf. Romans 3:25, Acts 17:30). This is not divine approval of paganism but patient tolerance. Now, through the gospel, God is calling all nations to repentance — the era of overlooked ignorance is ending', 'God approved of pagan worship', 'The nations were punished for walking in their own ways', 'This era of forbearance continues indefinitely', 'a', 'Acts 14:16 — "Who in times past suffered all nations to walk in their own ways." Compare Acts 17:30: "The times of this ignorance God winked at; but now commandeth all men every where to repent." The forbearance era is ending — the gospel inaugurates universal accountability.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 7, 'How does the phrase "opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles" (14:27) summarise the first missionary journey?', 'The metaphor of an "opened door" attributes the Gentile mission to God''s initiative — God opened the door, not Paul. Faith is the entry point, not circumcision or Torah observance. This summary statement prepares for the Jerusalem Council (chapter 15) where the question of Gentile admission will be formally debated. The first journey established the practical precedent', 'Paul opened the door through his eloquence', 'The door was opened by Roman political support', 'Faith was secondary to circumcision', 'a', 'Acts 14:27 — "How he had opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles." The subject is God ("he"), not Paul. The instrument is faith, not law. This report to Antioch documents what will become evidence at the Jerusalem Council (15:4,12): God Himself has acted to include Gentiles through faith alone.'),
('Acts', 14, 'adults', 8, 'What does Paul''s resilience after the Lystra stoning (rising and re-entering the city) demonstrate about apostolic commitment?', 'Paul''s return to the very city that stoned him demonstrates extraordinary courage and commitment to the mission. He did not seek vengeance or flee permanently but continued ministering. His later reference to "once was I stoned" (2 Corinthians 11:25) shows this was not forgotten. Paul embodied his own teaching that tribulation is the pathway to the kingdom', 'Paul returned because he forgot something', 'The stoning was not actually painful', 'Paul had nowhere else to go', 'a', 'Acts 14:20 — "He rose up, and came into the city: and the next day he departed with Barnabas to Derbe." Paul re-enters the city that just tried to kill him. He then retraces his steps through Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch (v.21) — revisiting places of persecution to strengthen disciples. The mission matters more than personal safety.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 15 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 15, 'kids', 1, 'What big question did the church leaders meet in Jerusalem to discuss?', 'Whether Gentile believers needed to be circumcised and follow the law of Moses to be saved', 'Whether to build a bigger church building', 'Whether Peter or Paul should be the leader', 'Whether to move the church to Rome', 'a', 'Acts 15:1,5-6 — "Except ye be circumcised after the manner of Moses, ye cannot be saved... But there rose up certain of the sect of the Pharisees which believed, saying, That it was needful to circumcise them, and to command them to keep the law of Moses."'),
('Acts', 15, 'kids', 2, 'What did the church leaders decide about the Gentile believers?', 'They should not be troubled with the law of Moses but should avoid idols, blood, things strangled, and fornication', 'They must follow every rule of Moses', 'They should become Jewish before becoming Christian', 'They should build their own separate churches', 'a', 'Acts 15:19-20 — "My sentence is, that we trouble not them, which from among the Gentiles are turned to God: But that we write unto them, that they abstain from pollutions of idols, and from fornication, and from things strangled, and from blood."'),
('Acts', 15, 'kids', 3, 'Why did Paul and Barnabas have a disagreement after the Jerusalem council?', 'They disagreed about whether to take John Mark on their next journey because he had left them before', 'They argued about which road to take', 'They could not agree on what to eat', 'They both wanted to visit the same city first', 'a', 'Acts 15:37-39 — "And Barnabas determined to take with them John, whose surname was Mark. But Paul thought not good to take him with them, who departed from them from Pamphylia, and went not with them to the work."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 15, 'teens', 1, 'What argument did Peter make at the Jerusalem Council?', 'God gave the Holy Ghost to the Gentiles just as He did to us, making no distinction — why put a yoke on them that neither our fathers nor we were able to bear? We believe that through the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ we shall be saved, even as they', 'Gentiles must follow the full law of Moses', 'Only Jewish Christians deserve the Holy Spirit', 'Peter sided with those demanding circumcision', 'a', 'Acts 15:8-11 — "God, which knoweth the hearts, bare them witness, giving them the Holy Ghost, even as he did unto us; And put no difference between us and them, purifying their hearts by faith... we believe that through the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ we shall be saved, even as they."'),
('Acts', 15, 'teens', 2, 'What evidence did Paul and Barnabas present to the council?', 'They declared all the miracles and wonders God had done among the Gentiles through them', 'They showed letters from Roman officials supporting them', 'They presented a list of Gentile donations', 'They argued from their own authority as apostles', 'a', 'Acts 15:12 — "Then all the multitude kept silence, and gave audience to Barnabas and Paul, declaring what miracles and wonders God had wrought among the Gentiles by them."'),
('Acts', 15, 'teens', 3, 'What Old Testament prophecy did James quote to support Gentile inclusion?', 'Amos 9:11-12 about rebuilding the tabernacle of David so that the rest of mankind may seek after the Lord, including all the Gentiles who are called by His name', 'Genesis 12 about Abraham''s calling', 'Psalm 22 about the suffering Messiah', 'Ezekiel 37 about the valley of dry bones', 'a', 'Acts 15:16-17 — "After this I will return, and will build again the tabernacle of David, which is fallen down... That the residue of men might seek after the Lord, and all the Gentiles, upon whom my name is called."'),
('Acts', 15, 'teens', 4, 'What was the result of the disagreement between Paul and Barnabas about John Mark?', 'They separated — Barnabas took Mark and sailed to Cyprus, while Paul chose Silas and went through Syria and Cilicia', 'They resolved the argument and stayed together', 'They asked the church to decide for them', 'Both of them retired from missionary work', 'a', 'Acts 15:39-40 — "And the contention was so sharp between them, that they departed asunder one from the other: and so Barnabas took Mark, and sailed unto Cyprus; And Paul chose Silas, and departed."'),
('Acts', 15, 'teens', 5, 'How was the council''s decision communicated to the Gentile churches?', 'They sent a letter with Judas and Silas to Antioch, saying "it seemed good to the Holy Ghost, and to us, to lay upon you no greater burden than these necessary things"', 'Peter personally visited every church', 'They sent a messenger on horseback to Rome', 'They posted the decision on the temple wall', 'a', 'Acts 15:25,28 — "It seemed good unto us... to send chosen men unto you... For it seemed good to the Holy Ghost, and to us, to lay upon you no greater burden than these necessary things."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 1, 'Why is the Jerusalem Council the most important ecclesiastical event in Acts?', 'It formally resolved the most critical theological question in early Christianity: the terms of Gentile salvation. The decision that Gentiles are saved by grace through faith without requiring circumcision or Torah observance preserved the gospel of grace and prevented Christianity from becoming a Jewish sect. Every subsequent Pauline mission depends on this decision', 'It was a minor administrative meeting', 'The question had already been settled', 'Only local churches were affected', 'a', 'Acts 15 resolves the question that could have destroyed the church: must Gentiles become Jews to be saved? The unanimous answer — no — preserves the universal gospel. Without this decision, Christianity would have remained a subset of Judaism, and the Gentile mission would have been impossible.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 2, 'How does Peter''s argument at the council ground Gentile inclusion in both experience and theology?', 'Peter cites experience (God gave Gentiles the Spirit, 15:8), makes a theological argument (God purified their hearts by faith, not by law, 15:9), and concludes with a grace-alone soteriology (salvation is through grace for Jews and Gentiles equally, 15:11). Remarkably, Peter says Jews are saved "even as they" — putting Jewish salvation on Gentile terms, not vice versa', 'Peter only used emotional arguments', 'Peter argued for circumcision', 'Peter''s argument was rejected by the council', 'a', 'Acts 15:8-11 — Peter''s threefold argument: (1) Experiential: "God gave them the Holy Ghost, even as he did unto us" (v.8); (2) Theological: "purifying their hearts by faith" (v.9); (3) Soteriological: "through the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ we shall be saved, even as they" (v.11). The last phrase is revolutionary — Jews saved like Gentiles, not vice versa.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 3, 'What are the four prohibitions in the apostolic decree (15:20,29), and why were these specific items chosen?', 'The four prohibitions — food sacrificed to idols, blood, things strangled, and sexual immorality — represent either Noahide laws (Genesis 9) binding on all humanity, or Leviticus 17-18 requirements for Gentiles living among Israel. They are minimum requirements for table fellowship between Jewish and Gentile believers, not salvation requirements. They preserved community unity', 'They are the minimum requirements for salvation', 'They were randomly selected', 'Only sexual immorality had moral significance', 'a', 'Acts 15:20,29 — The four items correspond to Leviticus 17-18 regulations for resident aliens (ger): idolatry (Lev 17:8-9), blood consumption (Lev 17:10-12), strangled animals (Lev 17:13-14), and sexual immorality (Lev 18). These enabled Jewish-Gentile table fellowship — the practical expression of theological unity.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 4, 'What does the phrase "it seemed good to the Holy Ghost, and to us" (15:28) reveal about apostolic decision-making?', 'The phrase claims divine-human cooperation in the council''s decision — the Holy Spirit''s guidance working through communal deliberation. The council did not receive a direct oracle but discerned the Spirit''s direction through testimony (Peter, Paul, Barnabas), Scripture (James citing Amos), and communal agreement. This establishes a model for Spirit-led institutional decision-making', 'The Holy Spirit dictated the letter word for word', 'The phrase was diplomatic rhetoric with no spiritual reality', 'Only James made the decision', 'a', 'Acts 15:28 — "It seemed good to the Holy Ghost, and to us." This remarkable formula combines Spirit and community. The process included: apostolic testimony (Peter, v.7-11), missionary evidence (Paul/Barnabas, v.12), scriptural argument (James, v.13-21), and communal agreement (v.22,25). The Spirit works through, not apart from, deliberation.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 5, 'How does James''s use of Amos 9:11-12 support the council''s decision?', 'James quotes Amos''s prophecy that God will rebuild David''s fallen tabernacle so that "the residue of men might seek after the Lord, and all the Gentiles, upon whom my name is called." James argues that Gentile inclusion was always part of God''s prophetic plan — it is not an innovation but a fulfilment. The rebuilt Davidic kingdom includes Gentiles by divine design', 'James misquoted Amos', 'Amos was speaking only about Israel''s national restoration', 'The quotation contradicted the council''s decision', 'a', 'Acts 15:15-18 — James says "to this agree the words of the prophets" and quotes Amos 9:11-12 (LXX). The key: Gentiles are "called by my name" — they belong to God as Gentiles, not as converts to Judaism. James provides the scriptural warrant for what Peter described experientially and Paul demonstrated practically.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 6, 'What does the Paul-Barnabas separation (15:36-41) teach about conflict in Christian ministry?', 'Even Spirit-filled leaders can sharply disagree — the "contention was so sharp" (paroxusmos) that they separated. Yet Luke does not condemn either party. The result was two mission teams instead of one (Paul-Silas to Asia Minor; Barnabas-Mark to Cyprus). God''s sovereignty can use even human conflict to advance the mission. Paul later reconciles with Mark (2 Timothy 4:11)', 'The separation was a catastrophic failure', 'Paul was completely right and Barnabas was wrong', 'Barnabas abandoned the mission entirely', 'a', 'Acts 15:39 — "The contention was so sharp between them, that they departed asunder." The word paroxusmos is strong (it gives us "paroxysm"). Yet providence multiplies the mission: two teams cover more ground. Paul''s later affirmation of Mark (Colossians 4:10, 2 Timothy 4:11) shows eventual reconciliation.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 7, 'How does the Jerusalem Council balance continuity with Judaism and freedom in Christ?', 'The council maintains continuity by not abolishing the law for Jewish believers (James still values Moses, v.21) while granting freedom to Gentile believers. The four prohibitions are minimal boundary markers that enable fellowship without imposing full Torah observance. The result is a "third way" — neither pure Torah observance nor lawless antinomianism, but grace-based community with practical love', 'The council abolished all Jewish law', 'The council required full Torah observance for all', 'No compromise was reached', 'a', 'Acts 15:19-21 — James''s "sentence" (krinein = judgment) treads carefully: "trouble not" Gentiles (freedom), but observe four practices (community sensitivity), because "Moses... hath in every city them that preach him" (awareness of Jewish sensibilities). The decree balances theological freedom with relational wisdom.'),
('Acts', 15, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of the letter being addressed to "the brethren which are of the Gentiles in Antioch and Syria and Cilicia" (15:23)?', 'The address acknowledges Gentile believers as "brethren" — full siblings in the faith, not second-class members. The geographic scope (Antioch, Syria, Cilicia) targets the regions where the circumcision controversy was most acute. The letter format — a formal decree from Jerusalem — gives the decision institutional authority and provides Gentile churches with a written document to counter Judaising pressure', 'The letter was a private note with no authority', 'Only Antioch was addressed', 'The term "brethren" excluded Gentiles', 'a', 'Acts 15:23 — "The apostles and elders and brethren send greeting unto the brethren which are of the Gentiles." Calling Gentiles "brethren" is theologically loaded — it affirms their full membership in the covenant community. The letter provides written, authoritative backing for Gentile freedom.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 16–18 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 16 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 16, 'kids', 1, 'What young man did Paul invite to join his missionary team?', 'Timothy, whose mother was a Jewish believer', 'John Mark, who had left them before', 'Barnabas, his old partner', 'Luke, the doctor', 'a', 'Acts 16:1-3 — "Then came he to Derbe and Lystra: and, behold, a certain disciple was there, named Timotheus, the son of a certain woman, which was a Jewess, and believed... Him would Paul have to go forth with him."'),
('Acts', 16, 'kids', 2, 'What happened to Paul and Silas in prison at Philippi at midnight?', 'They were praying and singing hymns to God, and suddenly a great earthquake shook the prison and all the doors opened', 'They fell asleep peacefully', 'The guards let them go quietly', 'A fire broke out and they escaped', 'a', 'Acts 16:25-26 — "And at midnight Paul and Silas prayed, and sang praises unto God... And suddenly there was a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison were shaken: and immediately all the doors were opened, and every one''s bands were loosed."'),
('Acts', 16, 'kids', 3, 'What did the Philippian jailer ask Paul and Silas?', 'Sirs, what must I do to be saved?', 'How did you open the prison doors?', 'Why were you singing so loudly?', 'Can you teach me to sing?', 'a', 'Acts 16:30 — "And brought them out, and said, Sirs, what must I do to be saved?"'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 16, 'teens', 1, 'How did God direct Paul to go to Macedonia?', 'Paul had a vision at night of a man from Macedonia pleading "Come over into Macedonia, and help us"', 'An angel appeared in the temple', 'A letter arrived from Macedonia', 'Paul had always planned to go there', 'a', 'Acts 16:9 — "And a vision appeared to Paul in the night; There stood a man of Macedonia, and prayed him, saying, Come over into Macedonia, and help us."'),
('Acts', 16, 'teens', 2, 'Who was Lydia, and how did she become a believer?', 'A seller of purple cloth from Thyatira who worshipped God — the Lord opened her heart to respond to Paul''s message, and she and her household were baptised', 'A Roman official who invited Paul to her palace', 'A Jewish priestess at the temple', 'A slave girl who served in a household', 'a', 'Acts 16:14-15 — "And a certain woman named Lydia, a seller of purple, of the city of Thyatira, which worshipped God, heard us: whose heart the Lord opened, that she attended unto the things which were spoken of Paul. And when she was baptized, and her household."'),
('Acts', 16, 'teens', 3, 'Why were Paul and Silas thrown into prison at Philippi?', 'They cast a spirit of divination out of a slave girl, and her masters were angry because they lost their source of income from her fortune-telling', 'They preached without a Roman permit', 'They refused to pay taxes to the city', 'They caused a riot in the marketplace', 'a', 'Acts 16:16-19 — "A certain damsel possessed with a spirit of divination... which brought her masters much gain by soothsaying... And when her masters saw that the hope of their gains was gone, they caught Paul and Silas, and drew them into the marketplace unto the rulers."'),
('Acts', 16, 'teens', 4, 'What answer did Paul and Silas give to the jailer''s question about being saved?', 'Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved, and thy house', 'Follow the law of Moses perfectly', 'Give all your money to the poor', 'Do good deeds every day of your life', 'a', 'Acts 16:31 — "And they said, Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved, and thy house."'),
('Acts', 16, 'teens', 5, 'Why did Paul refuse to leave prison quietly the next morning?', 'Because he and Silas were Roman citizens who had been beaten and imprisoned publicly without a trial — Paul demanded that the magistrates come personally to release them', 'He was too tired to leave early', 'He wanted to finish preaching to the prisoners', 'He did not trust the guards to let them go safely', 'a', 'Acts 16:37 — "They have beaten us openly uncondemned, being Romans, and have cast us into prison; and now do they thrust us out privily? nay verily; but let them come themselves and fetch us out."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 1, 'What does the Macedonian vision (16:9-10) reveal about divine guidance in mission?', 'The vision comes after the Spirit had blocked Paul twice (forbidden by the Holy Ghost in Asia, v.6; the Spirit suffered them not in Bithynia, v.7). God guides through both negative constraints (closed doors) and positive direction (the vision). Paul''s obedience to the vision brings the gospel to Europe for the first time — a pivotal moment in world history', 'Paul planned the entire route himself', 'The vision was just a dream with no significance', 'The Spirit never blocked Paul''s plans', 'a', 'Acts 16:6-10 — Two divine blockages (v.6-7) followed by a positive vision (v.9). The "we" narrative begins at v.10 (Luke joins the team). God''s guidance is both negative (closed doors) and positive (open doors). The result: the gospel enters Europe — arguably the most consequential geographic move in church history.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 2, 'What does the phrase "whose heart the Lord opened" (16:14) teach about the nature of conversion?', 'Luke attributes Lydia''s response to divine initiative — "the Lord opened her heart." While Lydia was already a God-fearer who "worshipped God," she needed the Lord to open her heart to respond to Paul''s specific message about Jesus. Conversion requires both the proclaimed word (Paul''s preaching) and the Lord''s inner work (opening the heart). Human response follows divine initiative', 'Lydia opened her own heart through study', 'The phrase is merely poetic', 'Heart-opening was a medical procedure', 'a', 'Acts 16:14 — "Whose heart the Lord opened, that she attended unto the things which were spoken of Paul." The verb "opened" (dienoixen) is the same word used for opening the Scriptures (Luke 24:32) and opening understanding (Luke 24:45). God illuminates the heart so that the word can be received.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 3, 'How do the three Philippian conversions (Lydia, slave girl, jailer) illustrate the gospel''s universal reach?', 'The three converts represent a cross-section of Roman society: Lydia (wealthy businesswoman, Asian God-fearer), the slave girl (lowest social class, demon-possessed), and the jailer (Roman military middle class, pagan). The gospel reaches every stratum: rich and poor, free and slave, male and female, Jew-adjacent and pagan. Philippi is a microcosm of the universal gospel', 'Only Lydia''s conversion was important', 'The three conversions are unrelated', 'Paul targeted only wealthy converts', 'a', 'Acts 16:14,18,33 — Lydia (wealthy, religious, female, Asian); slave girl (powerless, exploited, female, possessed); jailer (Roman authority, male, pagan). Three conversions spanning the entire social spectrum demonstrate that the gospel is "the power of God unto salvation to every one that believeth" (Romans 1:16).'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of Paul asserting his Roman citizenship after the beating (16:37)?', 'Paul''s appeal to citizenship serves a strategic purpose: by demanding a public apology, he protects the fledgling Philippian church from future persecution. The magistrates'' fear of having violated a citizen''s rights ("they feared, when they heard that they were Romans," v.38) creates legal precedent that shields the believers. Paul uses legal tools for the church''s benefit, not personal vengeance', 'Paul was seeking revenge for his beating', 'Roman citizenship had no legal significance', 'Paul made up his citizenship', 'a', 'Acts 16:37-39 — By forcing the magistrates to acknowledge their illegal action (beating/imprisoning Roman citizens without trial violated the Lex Valeria and Lex Porcia), Paul establishes that the church is not a criminal organisation. The magistrates'' embarrassment provides a measure of protection for Lydia''s house church.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 5, 'What does "Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved" (16:31) mean as the most concise gospel summary in Acts?', 'This is the apostolic gospel distilled to its essence: the object of faith (the Lord Jesus Christ — divine Lord, historical Jesus, anointed Messiah), the nature of response (believe — personal trust, not mere intellectual assent), and the promise (thou shalt be saved — complete salvation). "And thy house" extends the promise to the household, anticipating household baptism (v.33)', 'Belief is merely intellectual agreement', 'Salvation requires additional works', 'Only the jailer could be saved', 'a', 'Acts 16:31 — The threefold title "Lord Jesus Christ" packs maximum Christology: Lord (divine authority), Jesus (human name, "God saves"), Christ (messianic office). "Believe" (pisteuson) is aorist imperative — a decisive act of trust. "Thou shalt be saved" is future passive — God effects the salvation. Grace from start to finish.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 6, 'What does Paul and Silas singing hymns at midnight in prison (16:25) reveal about the relationship between worship and suffering?', 'Worship in suffering demonstrates faith that transcends circumstances — Paul and Silas praise God not because of their situation but despite it. Their worship transforms the prison into a sanctuary. The other prisoners "heard them" (v.25) — suffering-worship becomes a witness. The earthquake follows the worship, suggesting that praise releases divine power', 'They sang to stay awake', 'Singing was a Roman prison custom', 'The hymns were a distraction technique', 'a', 'Acts 16:25 — "And at midnight Paul and Silas prayed, and sang praises unto God: and the prisoners heard them." Worship in chains echoes Psalm 42 ("Why art thou cast down?") and anticipates Paul''s later prison epistles (Philippians, written from this very city''s church). The prisoners'' listening makes worship a form of witness.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 7, 'How does the "we" section beginning at 16:10 affect the historical credibility of Acts?', 'The shift to first-person plural ("we") indicates Luke joined the team at Troas. These "we passages" (16:10-17, 20:5-15, 21:1-18, 27:1-28:16) signal eyewitness participation, significantly strengthening Acts'' historical reliability. Luke transitions from secondary reporting to personal testimony, providing a contemporaneous account of events he witnessed firsthand', 'The "we" is an editorial convention with no personal meaning', 'Luke was present throughout all of Acts', 'Someone else wrote the "we" sections', 'a', 'Acts 16:10 — "Immediately we endeavoured to go into Macedonia." The sudden shift from "they" to "we" indicates the author (Luke) joining the missionary team at Troas. The "we" sections are among the strongest evidence for Lukan authorship and eyewitness testimony in Acts.'),
('Acts', 16, 'adults', 8, 'What does the casting out of the slave girl''s spirit reveal about the relationship between truth and demonic testimony?', 'The spirit spoke truth — "these men are the servants of the most high God, which shew unto us the way of salvation" (v.17) — yet Paul was grieved and cast it out. This reveals that truth from demonic sources is still unacceptable because it creates false association between the gospel and the occult. Jesus similarly silenced demons who proclaimed His identity (Mark 1:24-25). The gospel needs no demonic endorsement', 'Paul should have accepted the free advertising', 'The spirit was helping the mission', 'Demons always lie', 'a', 'Acts 16:17-18 — "These men are the servants of the most high God." True words, wrong source. Paul was "grieved" (diaponeomai = deeply troubled). Like Jesus (Mark 1:25,34), Paul refuses demonic testimony because association with the occult contaminates the gospel''s credibility. Source matters as much as content.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 17 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 17, 'kids', 1, 'What did the people of Berea do when Paul preached to them?', 'They searched the Scriptures daily to see whether what Paul said was true', 'They immediately threw Paul out', 'They fell asleep during his sermon', 'They asked Paul to come back in a year', 'a', 'Acts 17:11 — "These were more noble than those in Thessalonica, in that they received the word with all readiness of mind, and searched the scriptures daily, whether those things were so."'),
('Acts', 17, 'kids', 2, 'What did Paul notice in the city of Athens?', 'An altar with the inscription "TO THE UNKNOWN GOD"', 'A beautiful garden with many flowers', 'A very tall tower reaching to the sky', 'A golden statue of a king', 'a', 'Acts 17:23 — "For as I passed by, and beheld your devotions, I found an altar with this inscription, TO THE UNKNOWN GOD."'),
('Acts', 17, 'kids', 3, 'What did Paul say God made from one blood?', 'All nations of men to dwell on all the face of the earth', 'Only the people of Israel', 'Only the people of Greece', 'Only kings and rulers', 'a', 'Acts 17:26 — "And hath made of one blood all nations of men for to dwell on all the face of the earth."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 17, 'teens', 1, 'Why were the Bereans called "more noble" than the Thessalonians?', 'They received the word with all readiness of mind and searched the Scriptures daily to verify what Paul taught — they combined openness with discernment', 'They were wealthier and more educated', 'They gave Paul more money', 'They built him a synagogue to preach in', 'a', 'Acts 17:11 — "These were more noble than those in Thessalonica, in that they received the word with all readiness of mind, and searched the scriptures daily, whether those things were so."'),
('Acts', 17, 'teens', 2, 'What two groups of Greek philosophers debated with Paul in Athens?', 'The Epicureans and the Stoics', 'The Platonists and the Aristotelians', 'The Cynics and the Sceptics', 'The Pythagoreans and the Sophists', 'a', 'Acts 17:18 — "Then certain philosophers of the Epicureans, and of the Stoicks, encountered him."'),
('Acts', 17, 'teens', 3, 'What did Paul say God now commands all men everywhere to do?', 'Repent — because He hath appointed a day in which He will judge the world in righteousness by that man whom He hath ordained, and He proved it by raising Him from the dead', 'Build temples in every city', 'Study Greek philosophy', 'Offer sacrifices to the unknown god', 'a', 'Acts 17:30-31 — "And the times of this ignorance God winked at; but now commandeth all men every where to repent: Because he hath appointed a day, in the which he will judge the world in righteousness by that man whom he hath ordained; whereof he hath given assurance unto all men, in that he hath raised him from the dead."'),
('Acts', 17, 'teens', 4, 'What accusation did the Thessalonian Jews make against Paul and Silas?', 'These men who have turned the world upside down have come here also, saying there is another king, one Jesus', 'They were selling illegal goods', 'They were Roman spies', 'They were stealing from the synagogue', 'a', 'Acts 17:6-7 — "These that have turned the world upside down are come hither also... and these all do contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is another king, one Jesus."'),
('Acts', 17, 'teens', 5, 'How did the Athenians react when Paul spoke about the resurrection of the dead?', 'Some mocked, some said "We will hear thee again," and some believed, including Dionysius and a woman named Damaris', 'Everyone believed immediately', 'They arrested Paul and threw him in prison', 'They all mocked and Paul fled the city', 'a', 'Acts 17:32-34 — "And when they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some mocked: and others said, We will hear thee again of this matter... Howbeit certain men clave unto him, and believed: among the which was Dionysius the Areopagite, and a woman named Damaris."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 1, 'How does Paul''s Areopagus speech (17:22-31) demonstrate a masterful contextualised approach to a pagan audience?', 'Paul engages Athens on its own terms: he begins with their religiosity (the unknown god altar), quotes their own poets (Aratus and possibly Cleanthes — "in him we live, and move, and have our being"), yet subverts pagan assumptions by proclaiming God as Creator, Judge, and resurrector. He builds bridges through common ground but drives toward the distinctly Christian claims of resurrection and judgment', 'Paul ignored Athenian culture entirely', 'He simply repeated his synagogue sermon', 'The speech compromised the gospel', 'a', 'Acts 17:22-31 — Paul''s method: observation (altar, v.23), common ground (God as Creator, v.24-26), pagan poets as pre-evangelistic witnesses (v.28), challenge to idolatry (v.29), and the uniquely Christian proclamation: repentance, judgment, and resurrection (vv.30-31). He is all things to all men without compromising content.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 2, 'What is the theological significance of Paul''s declaration that God "dwelleth not in temples made with hands" (17:24)?', 'Paul echoes Stephen''s argument (Acts 7:48) and Isaiah 66:1-2 to challenge both Jewish temple-centrism and Greek temple religion. The transcendent Creator cannot be contained in human constructions. This is both a bridge (Stoics agreed God pervaded all things) and a challenge (Epicureans separated gods from human affairs). Paul affirms both divine transcendence and immanence', 'Paul was only criticising Jewish worship', 'Greek temples were acceptable to God', 'Paul rejected all forms of worship', 'a', 'Acts 17:24-25 — "God that made the world and all things therein, seeing that he is Lord of heaven and earth, dwelleth not in temples made with hands; Neither is worshipped with men''s hands, as though he needed any thing." This challenges every religious system that domesticates God — Jewish, Greek, or otherwise.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 3, 'How does the "unknown god" altar function in Paul''s argument?', 'Paul uses the altar as a point of contact — the Athenians'' own acknowledgment of ignorance becomes the opening for revelation. He does not say they were already worshipping the true God unknowingly but rather: "Whom therefore ye ignorantly worship, him declare I unto you." He repurposes their confession of ignorance as a platform for the gospel of the known God', 'Paul was approving of idol worship', 'The Athenians were already Christians', 'The altar had no rhetorical significance', 'a', 'Acts 17:23 — "Whom therefore ye ignorantly worship, him declare I unto you." Paul''s genius: the altar proves Athens knows it does not know enough. Paul offers to fill the gap — not by affirming their worship but by replacing ignorance with revelation. It''s a bridge, not an endorsement.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 4, 'What does Paul''s quotation of pagan poets ("in him we live, and move, and have our being... we are also his offspring") accomplish?', 'Paul cites Epimenides of Crete and Aratus of Cilicia (Paul''s home region) to establish common ground — pagans themselves intuited truths about divine immanence and human dignity. By quoting their own authorities, Paul shows that general revelation confirms what special revelation explicitly teaches. Yet he radically reinterprets these insights in a monotheistic, creationist framework', 'Paul was endorsing paganism', 'The quotations are from the Old Testament', 'Paul invented these quotes himself', 'a', 'Acts 17:28 — "For in him we live, and move, and have our being; as certain also of your own poets have said, For we are also his offspring." Paul does not cite the poets as authoritative but as witnesses to general revelation — even pagans glimpsed truths about God. He then redirects: if we are God''s offspring, we should not worship gold/silver/stone images (v.29).'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 5, 'What does "the times of this ignorance God winked at" (17:30) mean theologically?', 'God exercised patient forbearance during the era before the gospel was widely proclaimed — He "overlooked" (huperidein) pagan ignorance in the sense of withholding immediate judgment, not approving of it. But "now" — with the resurrection as proof and the gospel being proclaimed — this era of forbearance ends. Universal accountability has arrived. All people everywhere are called to repent', 'God approved of pagan worship in the past', 'Ignorance permanently excuses sin', 'The times of ignorance have not ended', 'a', 'Acts 17:30 — "The times of this ignorance God winked at; but now commandeth all men every where to repent." "Winked at" (huperidein) means overlooked/passed over without full punishment — not approved. Compare Romans 3:25: God "passed over" former sins. The resurrection inaugurates a new epoch of universal accountability.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 6, 'What does "hath made of one blood all nations" (17:26) establish about human unity and dignity?', 'Paul affirms the common origin of all humanity — all nations derive from one source (Adam). This was counter-cultural in a society that classified people by ethnicity (Greek vs barbarian). It undergirds both human equality and universal accountability. If all humans share one origin, all share one Creator and one coming Judge. The doctrine of creation grounds the ethics of universal dignity', 'Paul was discussing blood types', 'Only Greeks were made from one blood', 'This was a common Greek philosophical idea', 'a', 'Acts 17:26 — "Hath made of one blood all nations of men for to dwell on all the face of the earth." Against Greek ethnocentrism and Roman imperialism, Paul declares universal human kinship rooted in creation. This doctrine — all people from one ancestor — levels all ethnic hierarchies and establishes universal accountability before one God.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 7, 'Why did the resurrection provoke mockery from the Athenian philosophers?', 'Greek philosophy generally viewed the body negatively — Plato taught that the soul''s escape from the body was salvation. The idea of bodily resurrection was therefore philosophically absurd to Greeks. Epicureans denied any afterlife; Stoics believed in the soul''s reabsorption into the cosmos. Bodily resurrection contradicted both schools. The gospel''s scandal was not moral but metaphysical', 'Greeks were familiar with resurrection and found it boring', 'Only uneducated people mocked', 'The resurrection was rejected because of translation issues', 'a', 'Acts 17:32 — "When they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some mocked." Greek dualism (body = prison, soul = divine) made resurrection absurd. Aeschylus had declared: "When the dust has drained the blood of a man, once he is slain, there is no resurrection." Paul''s proclamation cut against the deepest assumptions of Hellenistic thought.'),
('Acts', 17, 'adults', 8, 'How do the varied responses in Athens (mocking, postponing, believing) typify responses to the gospel throughout Acts?', 'Luke presents three categories of response: outright rejection ("some mocked"), indecision/deferral ("we will hear thee again"), and faith ("certain men clave unto him, and believed"). These three responses recur throughout Acts and mirror the parable of the sower — hard ground, shallow ground, and good ground. Luke does not present Athens as a failure but as a realistic picture of gospel reception', 'Athens was a complete failure for Paul', 'Everyone in Athens eventually believed', 'Luke only recorded the positive response', 'a', 'Acts 17:32-34 — Three responses: mockery (hard hearts), delay (divided hearts), faith (open hearts). This pattern appears in every city: some believe, some reject, some defer. Luke''s realism prevents both triumphalism and despair — the gospel always divides, and even small harvests (Dionysius, Damaris) are genuine victories.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 18 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 18, 'kids', 1, 'What job did Paul, Aquila, and Priscilla share?', 'They were tentmakers', 'They were fishermen', 'They were carpenters', 'They were farmers', 'a', 'Acts 18:3 — "And because he was of the same craft, he abode with them, and wrought: for by their occupation they were tentmakers."'),
('Acts', 18, 'kids', 2, 'What did the Lord tell Paul in a night vision in Corinth?', 'Be not afraid, but speak and hold not thy peace: for I am with thee, and no man shall hurt thee', 'Leave this city immediately', 'Build a church on this spot', 'Go back to Jerusalem', 'a', 'Acts 18:9-10 — "Then spake the Lord to Paul in the night by a vision, Be not afraid, but speak, and hold not thy peace: For I am with thee, and no man shall set on thee to hurt thee: for I have much people in this city."'),
('Acts', 18, 'kids', 3, 'Who was Apollos?', 'A man from Alexandria who was eloquent and mighty in the Scriptures', 'A Roman soldier who became a Christian', 'A fisherman from Galilee', 'A priest from the temple in Jerusalem', 'a', 'Acts 18:24 — "And a certain Jew named Apollos, born at Alexandria, an eloquent man, and mighty in the scriptures, came to Ephesus."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 18, 'teens', 1, 'Why did Aquila and Priscilla come to Corinth?', 'Emperor Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome', 'They were sent as missionaries by the Jerusalem church', 'They came to trade purple cloth', 'They were fleeing from persecution in Ephesus', 'a', 'Acts 18:2 — "And found a certain Jew named Aquila, born in Pontus, lately come from Italy, with his wife Priscilla; (because that Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome)."'),
('Acts', 18, 'teens', 2, 'What did Paul declare when the Jews in Corinth opposed him?', 'Your blood be upon your own heads; I am clean: from henceforth I will go unto the Gentiles', 'I will continue preaching only in the synagogue', 'I will ask the Romans to force you to listen', 'I give up and am going home to Tarsus', 'a', 'Acts 18:6 — "And when they opposed themselves, and blasphemed, he shook his raiment, and said unto them, Your blood be upon your own heads; I am clean: from henceforth I will go unto the Gentiles."'),
('Acts', 18, 'teens', 3, 'How long did Paul stay in Corinth?', 'A year and six months, teaching the word of God among them', 'Three months', 'One week', 'Five years', 'a', 'Acts 18:11 — "And he continued there a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them."'),
('Acts', 18, 'teens', 4, 'What did Gallio the Roman proconsul decide about the Jews'' complaint against Paul?', 'He refused to judge the matter, saying it was about Jewish law and not a Roman crime — and drove them from the judgment seat', 'He sentenced Paul to prison', 'He ordered Paul to leave Corinth', 'He became a Christian and helped Paul', 'a', 'Acts 18:14-16 — "If it were a matter of wrong or wicked lewdness, O ye Jews, reason would that I should bear with you: But if it be a question of words and names, and of your law, look ye to it; for I will be no judge of such matters. And he drave them from the judgment seat."'),
('Acts', 18, 'teens', 5, 'What did Priscilla and Aquila do for Apollos?', 'They took him aside and expounded unto him the way of God more perfectly — teaching him about Jesus and baptism in the Holy Spirit', 'They gave him money to start a church', 'They sent him back to Alexandria', 'They asked him to stop preaching', 'a', 'Acts 18:26 — "And he began to speak boldly in the synagogue: whom when Aquila and Priscilla had heard, they took him unto them, and expounded unto him the way of God more perfectly."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 1, 'What does Paul''s tentmaking ministry (18:3) reveal about his philosophy of mission?', 'Paul worked to support himself to avoid being a financial burden and to model self-sufficiency (cf. 1 Thessalonians 2:9, 2 Thessalonians 3:8). His manual labour also gave him natural access to the marketplace and credibility as a working man. He chose financial independence to remove any accusation of preaching for profit and to provide a model for new believers', 'Paul was forced to work because no one supported him', 'Tentmaking was his primary calling', 'Manual labour was disgraceful for a rabbi', 'a', 'Acts 18:3 — Paul worked as a tentmaker (skenopoios — likely leather-working). He later defended this practice in 1 Corinthians 9:12-15 and 2 Corinthians 11:7-9. It was strategic: financial independence, marketplace access, and modelling work ethic for converts from cultures that devalued manual labour.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 2, 'What does the Lord''s night vision to Paul (18:9-10) reveal about the human side of apostolic ministry?', 'The vision implies Paul was afraid — otherwise the command "be not afraid" would be unnecessary. Even the great apostle experienced fear and discouragement. After Athens'' modest response and Corinth''s initial opposition, Paul needed divine encouragement. The Lord''s promise ("I have much people in this city") sustains mission with the assurance that God has already prepared a harvest', 'Paul was never afraid', 'The vision was Paul''s imagination', 'Fear is incompatible with faith', 'a', 'Acts 18:9-10 — "Be not afraid, but speak, and hold not thy peace." The command presupposes fear. Paul — stoned at Lystra, imprisoned at Philippi, chased from Thessalonica and Berea, mocked at Athens — needed reassurance. "I have much people in this city" (v.10) reveals divine foreknowledge: converts are already appointed.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 3, 'What is the significance of Gallio''s ruling for the legal status of early Christianity?', 'Gallio''s dismissal of the case effectively treated Christianity as an internal Jewish matter — a religio licita (legal religion) under the umbrella of Judaism. This set an informal legal precedent: Roman officials should not prosecute Christians for religious beliefs. Gallio''s ruling gave Paul (and Christianity) de facto legal protection throughout the province of Achaia', 'Gallio was sympathetic to Christianity', 'The ruling had no lasting impact', 'Gallio condemned Paul', 'a', 'Acts 18:14-16 — Gallio refused jurisdiction over an intra-Jewish religious dispute. Since Corinth was the capital of Achaia, his ruling had province-wide implications. Luke carefully records Roman officials (Gallio, Festus, Agrippa) finding Paul innocent, building a legal-apologetic case that Christianity was not a threat to Rome.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 4, 'What does the Apollos episode (18:24-28) teach about the relationship between knowledge, boldness, and teachability?', 'Apollos was eloquent, scripturally knowledgeable, and bold — yet his understanding was incomplete ("knowing only the baptism of John"). When Priscilla and Aquila privately instructed him, he accepted correction with humility. The episode shows that spiritual gifts and rhetorical skill need theological precision, and that even gifted leaders need ongoing formation by the body of Christ', 'Apollos was uneducated and needed basic instruction', 'Priscilla and Aquila publicly rebuked him', 'Apollos rejected their teaching', 'a', 'Acts 18:24-26 — Apollos: "eloquent" (logios), "mighty in the scriptures," "instructed in the way of the Lord," "fervent in the spirit," spoke "boldly" — yet needed "the way of God more perfectly." Priscilla and Aquila''s private instruction (not public correction) models gracious discipleship of gifted but incomplete leaders.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 5, 'What is the significance of Priscilla being named before Aquila in 18:26?', 'Luke and Paul (Romans 16:3, 2 Timothy 4:19) often name Priscilla first, suggesting she was the more prominent teacher or had higher social status. Her leading role in teaching Apollos — a gifted male preacher — demonstrates that women exercised significant teaching ministry in the early church. The couple models collaborative, private theological mentoring', 'The name order is alphabetical and meaningless', 'Only Aquila did the teaching', 'Luke made a scribal error', 'a', 'Acts 18:26 — "Aquila and Priscilla" (v.2) but "Priscilla and Aquila" (v.26, also Romans 16:3, 2 Timothy 4:19). Name order reversal in ancient texts typically indicates prominence. Priscilla''s leading role in instructing the eloquent Apollos is one of the clearest examples of female teaching ministry in the New Testament.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 6, 'How does Paul''s declaration "from henceforth I will go unto the Gentiles" (18:6) relate to his overall synagogue-first strategy?', 'This declaration occurs in Corinth specifically (as in 13:46 for Antioch of Pisidia). Paul does not permanently abandon Jews — he returns to synagogues in later cities (18:19, 19:8). Each "turning to Gentiles" is local, not global. The pattern shows Paul fulfilling his covenantal obligation to offer the gospel to Jews first in each city, then turning to Gentiles upon rejection', 'Paul permanently stopped preaching to Jews', 'This was the first time Paul turned to Gentiles', 'Paul never preached to Jews again after Corinth', 'a', 'Acts 18:6 — "From henceforth I will go unto the Gentiles." But Paul enters the Ephesian synagogue in 18:19 and 19:8. The turning-to-Gentiles declarations (13:46, 18:6, 28:28) are local, not absolute. Paul''s pattern: synagogue → rejection → Gentile mission in each city. Romans 1:16 ("to the Jew first") remains his operative principle.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 7, 'What does "I have much people in this city" (18:10) reveal about divine election and mission?', 'God tells Paul that He already has "much people" (laos polus) in Corinth — people not yet converted but already chosen. This motivates mission: Paul''s preaching will not fail because God has prepared a harvest. Divine election is the ground of missionary confidence, not a reason for passivity. Because God has chosen many, Paul should preach boldly', 'The phrase refers to people already converted', 'Election makes preaching unnecessary', 'God had no people in Corinth', 'a', 'Acts 18:10 — "I have much people (laos polus) in this city." God uses the covenant term "people" (laos, His special people) for those not yet converted. This echoes John 10:16 ("other sheep I have, which are not of this fold"). Election motivates rather than negates evangelism: preach, because God has prepared hearers.'),
('Acts', 18, 'adults', 8, 'How does Acts 18 mark the end of the second missionary journey and what has been accomplished?', 'Paul returns to Antioch (v.22) having established churches across Macedonia and Achaia (Philippi, Thessalonica, Berea, Athens, Corinth). The gospel has crossed from Asia to Europe, reached major cultural centres (Athens) and commercial hubs (Corinth), and gained de facto Roman legal protection (Gallio ruling). Christianity is now a trans-continental movement with a growing network of churches', 'The second journey was a failure', 'No new churches were established', 'Paul returned to Jerusalem only', 'a', 'Acts 18:22 — Paul''s return to Antioch completes the second journey (15:36-18:22). Achievements: churches in Philippi, Thessalonica, Berea, Corinth; contacts in Athens; the Gallio precedent; the Priscilla/Aquila partnership; and Apollos prepared for ministry. The Gentile church now spans two continents.');
